    "category": "AWS",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "How do S3 Bucket Policies and IAM User/Role Policies interact? How do you ensure an S3 bucket is completely blocked from public access?",
    "answer": "S3 access authorization is determined by the union of IAM Policies, S3 Bucket Policies, and ACLs. \n\n- **Interaction**: An explicit `DENY` in either policy always overrides an `ALLOW`. Access is granted only if there is an implicit or explicit `ALLOW` in at least one policy and no `DENY` anywhere.\n- **Blocking Public Access**: The most reliable way is enabling **S3 Block Public Access** at the bucket or account level. This acts as a master guardrail. Via AWS CLI:\n  ```bash\n  aws s3api put-public-access-block \\\n      --bucket my-secure-bucket \\\n      --public-access-block-configuration \"BlockPublicAcls=true,IgnorePublicAcls=true,BlockPublicPolicy=true,RestrictPublicBuckets=true\"\n  ```\nThis blocks the creation of public ACLs or policies and ignores existing ones, preventing accidental data exposure.",
    "tags": [
      "S3",
      "Security",
      "IAM",
      "Bucket Policy",
      "CLI"
    ]
