    "id": "linux-2",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "What is a zombie process in Linux, how do you identify it using CLI tools, and what is the proper way to clean it up?",
    "answer": "A zombie process is a process that has completed execution (via exit system call) but still has an entry in the process table. This occurs because the parent process has not yet read the child's exit status using wait() or waitpid(). While zombies do not consume CPU or memory resources, they consume a Process ID (PID) from the finite pool of PIDs.\n\nTo identify zombie processes, run:\n`ps aux | grep 'Z'` or `ps -eo stat,pid,ppid,comm | grep -w Z`\nIn top, the header shows the count of zombie processes, and they appear with state 'Z'.\n\nTo clean up a zombie process:\n1. Since the zombie process is already dead (terminated), you cannot kill it with SIGKILL (kill -9).\n2. You must notify the parent process to reap the zombie. Send a SIGCHLD signal to the parent:\n`kill -s SIGCHLD <parent_pid>`\n3. If the parent is poorly written and ignores SIGCHLD, you must terminate the parent process itself:\n`kill -15 <parent_pid>` (or `kill -9 <parent_pid>` if it doesn't respond).\n4. When the parent dies, the zombie process is adopted by init/systemd (PID 1), which periodically calls wait() to reap orphans.",
    "tags": [
      "process",
      "zombie",
      "sys_wait",
      "ps",
      "signals"
    ]
