    "question": "How do you check disk space utilization and find the largest directories on a Linux filesystem? Provide CLI commands.",
    "answer": "To check overall disk utilization across all mounted filesystems, use `df` (disk free):\n`df -h` (human-readable format, e.g., GB/MB)\n`df -i` (checks inode utilization instead of block storage, crucial because running out of inodes prevents file creation even if there is free space).\n\nTo identify the largest directories or files in a specific directory (e.g., `/var`), use `du` (disk usage):\n`du -sh /var/* | sort -h`\n- `-s`: Summary (only output total for each argument).\n- `-h`: Human-readable format.\n- `sort -h`: Sorts numerically by human-readable suffixes (K, M, G).\n\nTo find the top 10 largest files recursively on a filesystem:\n`find / -type f -exec du -Sh {} + | sort -rh | head -n 10`\nAlternatively, use the interactive `ncdu` (NCurses Disk Usage) tool if installed.",
