    "id": "linux-7",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "How do you view and modify Linux kernel parameters temporarily and permanently? Give examples.",
    "answer": "Linux kernel parameters are exposed via the `/proc/sys/` virtual directory and are managed using the `sysctl` command.\n\n**Temporarily View Parameters**:\n- View all parameters: `sysctl -a`\n- View a specific parameter (e.g., max connections): `sysctl net.core.somaxconn` or `cat /proc/sys/net/core/somaxconn`\n\n**Temporarily Modify Parameters (lost on reboot)**:\n- Using sysctl: `sudo sysctl -w net.core.somaxconn=4096`\n- Writing directly to procfs: `echo 4096 | sudo tee /proc/sys/net/core/somaxconn`\n\n**Permanently Modify Parameters (survives reboot)**:\nAdd the configuration line to `/etc/sysctl.conf` or a file in `/etc/sysctl.d/`:\n```text\nnet.core.somaxconn = 4096\n```\nApply the changes immediately from the configuration file without rebooting:\n`sudo sysctl -p /etc/sysctl.d/99-custom.conf`",
