    "id": "linux-9",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "How do you check memory and swap utilization in Linux, and what does the 'buff/cache' field in the output of free represent?",
    "answer": "To check memory and swap utilization, run `free -m` (in megabytes) or `free -g` (in gigabytes).\n\nIn the output of `free`, memory is split into columns:\n- **total**: Total physical RAM installed.\n- **used**: Memory currently allocated by processes (Calculated as `total - free - buffers - cache`).\n- **free**: Unused memory that is completely empty.\n- **shared**: Memory used by tmpfs (shmem).\n- **buff/cache**: Combined filesystem buffers and page cache.\n  - *Buffers*: Disk block metadata storage (e.g., directories, permissions) temporarily kept in RAM.\n  - *Cache*: Cached pages of files read from disk. The Linux kernel uses otherwise free RAM to cache files to speed up subsequent reads. This memory is not wasted; it is immediately reclaimed and allocated to applications if they request it.\n- **available**: An estimate of how much memory is available for starting new applications without swapping. Unlike 'free', it includes the reclaimable portions of the page cache.",
    "tags": [
      "free",
      "memory",
      "swap",
      "page-cache",
      "buffers"
    ]
