    "id": "linux-12",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "How do you inspect logs of systemd services and view boot logs using journalctl? Provide common command examples.",
    "answer": "`journalctl` queries the systemd-journald service logs. Common query combinations:\n\n- **Follow logs in real-time (similar to tail -f)**:\n  `journalctl -u nginx.service -f`\n- **Filter logs for a specific service since a relative time offset**:\n  `journalctl -u nginx.service --since \"2 hours ago\"`\n- **Show logs with high priority (errors, critical, alerts)**:\n  `journalctl -p err -u nginx.service`\n- **View logs for the current boot session**:\n  `journalctl -b`\n- **View logs for the previous boot session (useful for post-crash debugging)**:\n  `journalctl -b -1`\n- **Output logs in JSON format for external parsing**:\n  `journalctl -u nginx.service -o json-pretty -n 10`\n- **View kernel ring buffer logs (similar to dmesg)**:\n  `journalctl -k`",
