    "id": "linux-14",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "Explain the role of `/etc/hosts` and `/etc/nsswitch.conf` in local name resolution before querying external DNS servers.",
    "answer": "Before resolving domain names via external DNS servers, the operating system checks local configurations to determine resolve order.\n\n- **`/etc/hosts`**: A static local text table mapping IP addresses to hostnames. It allows mapping custom overrides without querying DNS nameservers. Format:\n  `127.0.0.1  localhost`\n  `10.0.0.50  db-primary.internal`\n\n- **`/etc/nsswitch.conf` (Name Service Switch)**: Instructs the system which database sources to use for looking up names (hosts, users, groups) and in what order. SREs look at the `hosts` entry:\n  `hosts: files dns`\n  This tells the system: first check local files (meaning `/etc/hosts`), and if the domain is not found, proceed to query external DNS resolvers (configured in `/etc/resolv.conf`). Changing this order to `hosts: dns files` would cause local host overrides to be ignored if the external DNS has a mapping.",
