    "question": "Explain how Linux Traffic Control (tc) operates. Provide commands to simulate packet loss, network latency, and bandwidth limits on an interface.",
    "answer": "Linux Traffic Control (`tc`) manipulates the kernel's packet scheduling subsystems using queuing disciplines (qdiscs), classes, and filters. A qdisc acts as a scheduler that determines how egress packets are queued and transmitted out of a network card.\n\nTo simulate network impairments, SREs use the Netem (Network Emulator) qdisc:\n\n**1. Simulate Network Latency**:\nAdd a qdisc to eth0 that introduces 150ms of latency with 10ms of random jitter:\n`sudo tc qdisc add dev eth0 root netem delay 150ms 10ms`\n\n**2. Simulate Packet Loss**:\nAdd a qdisc that drops 5% of packets randomly:\n`sudo tc qdisc add dev eth0 root netem loss 5%`\n\n**3. Configure Bandwidth Limits (Rate Limiting)**:\nTo enforce strict bandwidth shaping (e.g., limit outgoing traffic on eth0 to 10Mbps), use a Token Bucket Filter (TBF) qdisc:\n`sudo tc qdisc add dev eth0 root tbf rate 10mbit burst 32kbit latency 400ms`\n- `rate 10mbit`: Maximum sustained output rate.\n- `burst`: Maximum bucket capacity for short-term bursts.\n- `latency`: Maximum packet delay waiting in the queue before being dropped.\n\n**4. Clear all tc rules on an interface**:\n`sudo tc qdisc del dev eth0 root`",
