    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "What is eBPF (Extended Berkeley Packet Filter)? How does it run inside the kernel, and what are its advantages over traditional kprobes?",
    "answer": "eBPF is a revolutionary technology that allows running sandboxed, user-defined programs inside the Linux kernel dynamically without modifying kernel source code or loading kernel modules.\n\n**How it runs inside the kernel**:\n1. A developer writes an eBPF program in C or Rust.\n2. The compiler generates eBPF bytecode.\n3. The user space loader loads the bytecode into the kernel using the `bpf()` system call.\n4. **Verifier**: A critical kernel verification engine inspects the code to ensure it is safe (contains no infinite loops, cannot crash the kernel, cannot access unauthorized memory, and always terminates).\n5. **JIT Compiler**: Compiles the verified bytecode into native CPU assembly instructions for maximum execution speed.\n6. The program executes when it hits attached kernel hook points (sockets, tracepoints, kprobes).\n\n**Advantages over traditional Kprobes/Uprobes**:\n- *Safety*: Traditional kprobes run raw kernel module code. If the code has a null pointer dereference, it panics and crashes the entire server. eBPF is guaranteed to be safe by the verifier.\n- *Performance*: eBPF programs can collect and aggregate data inside kernel space memory using BPF maps, returning only summarized data to user space. This avoids the massive context-switching overhead of transferring millions of events to user space for analysis.",
