    "id": "linux-42",
    "category": "Linux",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "Detail filesystem journaling in ext4. Compare the performance and safety trade-offs of journal, ordered, and writeback modes.",
    "answer": "Journaling protects filesystems from corruption due to crashes or power losses. Instead of writing files directly to disk block sectors, changes are first written to a dedicated journal log before being committed to the main filesystem.\n\nIn ext4, journaling is configured in mount options (`/etc/fstab`) with three modes:\n\n1. **`data=journal` (Safest, Slowest)**:\n   - Both file metadata and the actual file content (payload) are written to the journal before being written to the filesystem block sectors.\n   - *Trade-off*: Maximum data safety. In the event of a crash, you can recover both metadata and data completely. However, write throughput is cut in half because all data is written to disk twice.\n\n2. **`data=ordered` (Default)**:\n   - Only filesystem metadata changes are written to the journal. However, the kernel forces the actual file data blocks to be written to disk *before* the metadata changes are committed to the journal.\n   - *Trade-off*: Prevents 'stale data read' vulnerabilities (where a file looks complete but contains old deleted data blocks after a crash). Good compromise between safety and write speed.\n\n3. **`data=writeback` (Fastest, Riskiest)**:\n   - Metadata is journaled, but there are no ordering guarantees. File data blocks can be written to disk after metadata is committed.\n   - *Trade-off*: Maximum I/O throughput. However, if the server crashes, metadata updates can point to file blocks that were never written, resulting in corrupt files containing junk data.",
    "tags": [
      "ext4",
      "journaling",
      "filesystem",
      "database-storage",
      "performance"
    ]
