    "id": "net-7",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "Differentiate between Layer 4 (L4) and Layer 7 (L7) load balancing. When should you use which?",
    "answer": "Load balancers distribute traffic across multiple backend servers, operating at different layers of the OSI model:\n\n**Layer 4 (L4) Load Balancing**:\n- Operates at the Transport layer (TCP/UDP).\n- *Mechanics*: Does not inspect packet payloads. It routes packets based on IP addresses and port numbers (e.g., incoming packet to IP X on port 80 is forwarded to backend Y on port 8080).\n- *Performance*: Fast and computationally lightweight because it doesn't decrypt TLS or parse HTTP headers.\n- *When to use*: For generic TCP/UDP workloads, database traffic (e.g., Postgres pool), or at the ingress point of an infrastructure where high raw throughput (Gbps) is required.\n\n**Layer 7 (L7) Load Balancing**:\n- Operates at the Application layer (HTTP/HTTPS/gRPC).\n- *Mechanics*: Terminates connections, decrypts TLS, and parses the actual HTTP request. It can route traffic based on URL paths (`/api` vs `/static`), headers, cookies, or request methods.\n- *Performance*: Slower and consumes more CPU because it must execute cryptographic handshakes and buffer request payloads.\n- *When to use*: For microservice routing, URL path-based routing, sticky sessions, TLS certificate termination, and web application firewalls (WAF).",
