    "id": "net-8",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "What are sticky sessions (session affinity) in load balancing? What are their advantages and disadvantages?",
    "answer": "Sticky sessions (session affinity) is a routing mechanism where a load balancer binds an end-user's session to a specific backend server. Subsequent requests from that user are routed to the same server for the duration of the session.\n\n**How it works**:\n- The load balancer inserts a tracking cookie (cookie-based affinity) or hashes the client's IP address (IP hash-based affinity).\n\n**Advantages**:\n- *Local Caching*: The backend server can store the user's session state (e.g., shopping cart, login tokens) in its local RAM cache, avoiding expensive lookups to a central database or external cache (Redis).\n- *Legacy App Support*: Allows scaling of legacy applications that are stateful and do not support distributed session stores.\n\n**Disadvantages**:\n- *Uneven Load Distribution*: Can lead to hotspots. If a few power-users (generating high traffic) are stuck to the same server, that server gets overloaded while others sit idle.\n- *Poor Fault Tolerance*: If a backend server crashes, all users stick to that server lose their session state and must log in again.\n- *Autoscaling Bottlenecks*: Newly spawned instances cannot take over existing active sessions, slowing down scale-out responsiveness.",
    "tags": [
      "load-balancing",
      "session-affinity",
      "sticky-sessions",
      "scaling"
    ]
