    "id": "net-15",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "Describe common DNS record types: A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, and TXT records. Give examples of their use.",
    "answer": "DNS zone files contain resource records that map hostnames to IP addresses or other data:\n\n- **A Record (Address)**: Maps a hostname to an IPv4 address.\n  - *Example*: `api.domain.com IN A 192.0.2.1`\n- **AAAA Record (IPv6 Address)**: Maps a hostname to an IPv6 address.\n  - *Example*: `api.domain.com IN AAAA 2001:db8::1`\n- **CNAME Record (Canonical Name)**: Maps an alias hostname to another canonical hostname. It triggers a secondary DNS lookup chain.\n  - *Example*: `www.domain.com IN CNAME domain.com` (useful when routing traffic to external endpoints like cloud load balancers: `lb.amazonaws.com`).\n- **MX Record (Mail Exchange)**: Specifies the mail servers responsible for receiving email for the domain, with a priority weight.\n  - *Example*: `domain.com IN MX 10 mail.domain.com`\n- **TXT Record (Text)**: Holds arbitrary text metadata. Commonly used for email authentication security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) or proving domain ownership to third-party providers (e.g., Google Search Console verification).\n  - *Example*: `domain.com IN TXT \"v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com ~all\"`",
