    "id": "net-26",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "What is IPsec? Explain the differences between Transport Mode and Tunnel Mode, and the roles of AH and ESP.",
    "answer": "IPsec is a suite of protocols used to secure IP communications by authenticating and encrypting each IP packet in a data stream.\n\n**Encapsulation Modes**:\n- **Transport Mode**:\n  - Only encrypts/authenticates the payload (data) of the IP packet. The original IP header is preserved.\n  - *Use Case*: End-to-end security between two hosts directly (e.g., host-to-host database connections).\n- **Tunnel Mode**:\n  - Encrypts both the payload and the original IP header. The entire packet is wrapped inside a new IP packet with a new outer IP header.\n  - *Use Case*: Site-to-site VPNs (e.g., connecting an office gateway to an AWS VPC transit gateway).\n\n**IPsec Protocols**:\n- **AH (Authentication Header)**: Provides data integrity and source authentication, but **no encryption** (payload is visible). It is rarely used in modern setups.\n- **ESP (Encapsulating Security Payload)**: Provides data integrity, source authentication, and **full encryption**, protecting packet contents from eavesdropping.",
