    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How does a reverse proxy handle TLS Connection Termination vs TLS Pass-through? Compare their security and operation.",
    "answer": "When hosting HTTPS applications behind a reverse proxy (e.g., Nginx, HAProxy), SREs configure how TLS connections are processed:\n\n**TLS Termination**:\n- The reverse proxy decrypts the incoming SSL/TLS traffic from the client. It inspects the HTTP headers and forwards the decrypted traffic as plain HTTP (or re-encrypted HTTPS) to the backend application servers.\n- *Pros*: Centralizes certificate management on the proxy (easy renewal). The proxy can inspect headers, block SQL injections (WAF), enforce cookies, and perform L7 routing.\n- *Cons*: Traffic between the proxy and the backend is unencrypted unless explicit secondary HTTPS is configured, presenting security concerns inside the VPC.\n\n**TLS Pass-through**:\n- The proxy does not decrypt the TLS session. It simply forwards the raw encrypted byte stream (Layer 4 TCP) to the backend servers based on the Server Name Indication (SNI) header.\n- *Pros*: Maximum security. The backend server owns the private key and decrypts the traffic, meaning the proxy never sees sensitive payloads.\n- *Cons*: Certificates must be distributed to all backend servers. The proxy cannot inspect HTTP headers, paths, or cookies, limiting routing to Layer 4 parameters.",
