    "question": "What is DNSSEC? How does it secure DNS queries against cache poisoning and spoofing?",
    "answer": "DNSSEC (Domain Name System Security Extensions) secures DNS lookup queries by cryptographically signing DNS records, ensuring data integrity and authenticity.\n\n**How it works**:\n- DNSSEC does **not** encrypt DNS queries (traffic remains visible). Instead, it adds public-key signatures (RRSIG records) to existing DNS records.\n- When a client queries a DNSSEC-enabled zone, the DNS server returns the requested record (e.g., A record) along with its corresponding cryptographic signature (RRSIG).\n- The resolver verifies the signature using the zone's Public Key (DNSKEY). To establish trust, the public key's validity is verified by a Chain of Trust leading up to the TLD and the root zone anchor key, using Delegation Signer (DS) records.\n\n**Mitigation**:\n- This prevents DNS cache poisoning (where an attacker injects a fake IP into a resolver's cache) because the resolver will reject any fake IP that does not have a matching cryptographic signature from the domain's authoritative key.",
