    "question": "What is Anycast routing? How do SREs use it to deploy highly available DNS and CDN networks?",
    "answer": "Anycast is a network routing technique where multiple physical servers located in different parts of the world share the exact same IP address.\n\n**How it works**:\n- These servers advertise the shared IP to the internet using BGP routing. Routers along the path select the shortest BGP path (lowest hop count) to route packets.\n- As a result, when a client connects to the Anycast IP, routers automatically forward the packets to the geographically closest server hosting that IP.\n\n**SRE Use Cases**:\n- **DNS Services (e.g., 8.8.8.8)**: Query traffic is routed to the closest DNS resolver PoP, minimizing query latency. If a PoP crashes, BGP routes automatically reconverge, sending traffic to the next closest active PoP without user-side configuration changes.\n- **CDNs**: Directs users to the nearest CDN Edge server for fast TLS termination.\n- **DDoS Mitigation**: Floods of attack traffic are naturally dispersed and diluted across multiple global nodes instead of concentrating on a single datacenter.",
