    "id": "net-32",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Differentiate between the TCP Congestion Window (cwnd) and the Receiver Window (rwnd). How do they interact to limit data transmission?",
    "answer": "Both `cwnd` and `rwnd` limit the amount of unacknowledged data a sender can transmit over a TCP socket, but they represent different network bottlenecks:\n\n- **Receiver Window (`rwnd`)**: Represents the available buffer space in RAM on the receiving host. It is advertised by the receiver in the TCP header to prevent the sender from overflowing its socket buffers (Flow Control).\n- **Congestion Window (`cwnd`)**: Represents the estimated capacity of the network links connecting the hosts, calculated dynamically by the sender's congestion control algorithm (e.g., BBR, CUBIC) to prevent network saturation (Congestion Control).\n\n**Interaction**: \nThe sender calculates the maximum allowed bytes in flight (the Transmission Window, `W`) as the minimum of the two variables:\n\n`W = min(cwnd, rwnd)`\n\nIf the network is fast but the receiving app is slow, `rwnd` governs transmission. If the receiver is fast but the network is congested (drops packets), `cwnd` shrinks and governs transmission.",
    "tags": [
      "tcp",
      "cwnd",
      "rwnd",
      "flow-control",
      "congestion-control"
    ]
