    "id": "net-36",
    "category": "Networking",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "What is a Split-Brain DNS configuration, and what are its security and operational benefits in enterprise infrastructures?",
    "answer": "Split-Brain (or Split-Horizon) DNS is a configuration where a DNS server returns different IP addresses for the same domain name depending on the source IP address of the requesting client.\n\n**How it is structured**:\n- **Internal View**: When a client inside the corporate network (or VPC) queries `db.company.com`, the DNS server resolves it to a private IP (e.g., `10.0.5.20`).\n- **External View**: When a client on the public internet queries the same domain, the DNS server either denies resolution entirely or resolves it to a public IP (e.g., the corporate VPN gateway or public load balancer).\n\n**Benefits**:\n1. **Security**: Hides internal network topology. Attackers scanning DNS records from the internet cannot discover private hostnames or IP addresses of internal databases and microservices.\n2. **Performance (Routing)**: Internal servers talk directly to each other via private subnets (saving data transfer costs and NAT Gateway bandwidth) instead of hair-pinning traffic out to the internet and back.",
