    "id": "docker-14",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "What is the difference between --cpus and --cpu-shares in Docker resource allocation?",
    "answer": "1. **`--cpus`**: Sets a hard limit on the fractional CPU resources a container can use. For instance, `--cpus=1.5` guarantees the container can consume at most 1.5 cores of total CPU runtime per CFS scheduler period, regardless of host load.\\n2. **`--cpu-shares`**: Sets a relative priority weighting (default is 1024). It is a soft limit. If the host CPU is idle, a container can use 100% of the CPU. However, if the CPU is congested, resources are allocated proportionally. A container with `--cpu-shares=2048` will receive twice the CPU time of a container with `--cpu-shares=1024`.",
