    "question": "How do you securely mount a build secret during image creation using BuildKit without exposing it in the layer history?",
    "answer": "With BuildKit, you can use the `--mount=type=secret` flag in your Dockerfile RUN commands. This temporarily mounts the secret into a RAM-backed filesystem during the execution of that specific RUN instruction. The secret is never written to any image layers or metadata.\\n\\nDockerfile Syntax:\\n```dockerfile\\n# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1\\nFROM python:3.10-slim\\nRUN --mount=type=secret,id=pip_conf \\\\n    pip install --config-file /run/secrets/pip_conf -r requirements.txt\\n```\\n\\nCLI Command to build:\\n```bash\\ndocker build --secret id=pip_conf,src=~/.pip/pip.conf -t my-app .\\n```",
