    "id": "docker-18",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Explain how BuildKit cache mounts work to speed up repetitive compilation/package download stages.",
    "answer": "BuildKit introduces `--mount=type=cache` within RUN instructions. This lets you specify a directory inside the container that will persist across successive builds. It behaves like a persistent cache volume that doesn't get flattened into the image layers.\\n\\nExample for Go compiler caching:\\n```dockerfile\\n# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1\\nFROM golang:1.21-alpine\\nWORKDIR /src\\nCOPY . .\\nRUN --mount=type=cache,target=/root/.cache/go-build \\\\n    --mount=type=cache,target=/go/pkg/mod \\\\n    go build -o /app/server .\\n```\\nThis configuration prevents re-downloading Go dependencies and optimizes compiler execution time during incremental CI/CD runs.",
