    "id": "docker-20",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "What architectural changes are introduced in Linux cgroups v2, and how do they benefit container resource isolation?",
    "answer": "Control Groups (cgroups) isolate resource usage (CPU, memory, I/O) for containers.\\n\\n**Cgroups v1 vs v2**:\\n1. **Single Unified Hierarchy**: In cgroups v1, each controller (CPU, Memory, Pids) was managed as an independent process tree, making resource collaboration difficult. Cgroups v2 organizes controllers in a unified directory structure under `/sys/fs/cgroup/`.\\n2. **Out-of-Memory (OOM) Handling**: Cgroups v2 supports the *OOM Killer Group* feature. Instead of killing random individual processes inside the container, the entire control group (container) is terminated atomically.\\n3. **PSI (Pressure Stall Information)**: Provides kernel metrics indicating resource starvation delays (CPU, Memory, I/O) before failures occur.",
    "tags": [
      "Linux",
      "Cgroups v2",
      "Resources"
    ]
