    "id": "docker-24",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Compare containerd CLI tools ctr and nerdctl. When would you use them?",
    "answer": "1. **`ctr`**: A low-level CLI packaged directly with containerd. It is intended for testing containerd features and debugging. It is not developer-friendly; it uses namespaces (e.g., `ctr -n k8s.io task list` for Kubernetes containers) and requires verbose command strings.\\n2. **`nerdctl`**: A docker-compatible CLI for containerd. It supports the same UX as Docker (e.g., `nerdctl run`, `nerdctl compose`, `nerdctl build`). It supports advanced containerd capabilities like lazy pulling (Starlight/eStargz), image signing (Cosign), and encrypted images.\\n\\n**Usage**: Use `ctr` on Kubernetes nodes for emergency low-level node debugging. Use `nerdctl` as a drop-in replacement for Docker CLI in container development.",
