    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How does Docker Registry Garbage Collection work, and what precautions must you take before executing it?",
    "answer": "When an image is overwritten or deleted from a registry, the reference is removed, but the actual filesystem blobs (layers) remain. This requires running Garbage Collection (GC).\\n\\n**Precautions**:\\n- **Read-Only Mode**: You *must* set the registry to read-only mode during GC. If a client pushes an image during GC, the garbage collector might delete incoming layers before the manifest is written, resulting in corrupt, unpullable images.\\n\\nCommand to run GC in the official registry container:\\n```bash\\nregistry garbage-collect /etc/docker/registry/config.yml --delete-untagged\\n```",
