    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "What is a seccomp profile in Docker, and how do you load a custom seccomp profile during container execution?",
    "answer": "Seccomp (Secure Computing Mode) is a Linux kernel feature that filters system calls (syscalls) made by processes. Docker has a default seccomp profile that blocks over 40 dangerous syscalls (like reboot, kexec_load, mount) out of ~300+.\\n\\nTo apply a custom JSON seccomp profile that restricts syscalls further (e.g., blocking `keyctl`), use the `--security-opt` flag:\\n```bash\\ndocker run --security-opt seccomp=/path/to/custom-seccomp.json -d app-image\\n```\\nThis restricts the container process at the kernel level, mitigating kernel exploitation vectors.",
