    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How do you configure the Docker daemon to authenticate with and trust a private registry using self-signed TLS certificates?",
    "answer": "To secure communications with a self-signed registry without bypassing certificate validation, you must install the registry's root CA certificate on the Docker host daemon.\\n\\nSteps:\\n1. Create the directory for the registry CA cert:\\n   `sudo mkdir -p /etc/docker/certs.d/myregistry.local:5000/`\\n2. Copy the registry root CA certificate (domain.crt) into that directory as `ca.crt`:\\n   `sudo cp domain.crt /etc/docker/certs.d/myregistry.local:5000/ca.crt`\\n3. Restart docker daemon: `sudo systemctl restart docker`.\\nIf you must bypass verification for testing, add it to `insecure-registries` in `/etc/docker/daemon.json`:\\n```json\\n{ \"insecure-registries\": [\"myregistry.local:5000\"] }\\n```",
