    "id": "docker-33",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How do you use the nsenter tool on a Linux host to run packet captures on a specific container?",
    "answer": "The `nsenter` tool allows you to enter the namespace of another process. Since containers are isolated Linux processes, you can enter a container's network namespace and run host tools (like `tcpdump`) without modifying the container image.\\n\\nSteps:\\n1. Find the PID of the container's primary process:\\n   `PID=$(docker inspect -f '{{.State.Pid}}' <container-id>)`\\n2. Run `nsenter` to enter the network namespace (`-n`) and run `tcpdump`:\\n   `sudo nsenter -t $PID -n tcpdump -i eth0 -vvv -w /tmp/capture.pcap`\\nThis captures raw traffic flowing through the container's virtual ethernet interface and writes it directly to the host's `/tmp` directory.",
