    "id": "docker-35",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Explain Docker registry manifest schema V2 and the concept of content addressability.",
    "answer": "Docker images are stored in registries as a collection of layers and a config JSON manifest. The Manifest V2 schema lists the image's layer digests (cryptographic hashes), size, and media type.\\n\\n**Content Addressability**: Images and layers are identified by their cryptographic hash (SHA256 digest of the content payload) rather than user-assigned tags. When pulling an image, Docker requests the manifest, retrieves the layer digests, and verifies the local filesystem layers against those digests. This guarantees that layer integrity is protected against tamper or transmission errors.",
    "tags": [
      "Registry",
      "Security",
      "Manifests"
    ]
