    "id": "docker-36",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How do you resolve permission mismatch issues (e.g. root-owned files created on host) during local directory bind mounting?",
    "answer": "By default, if a container process runs as root (UID 0), files it creates in a bind-mounted directory on the host are owned by root, breaking local user access.\\n\\n**Solutions**:\\n1. **Pass host UID/GID at runtime**: Match the container process UID/GID with the host user by passing the `-u` flag:\\n   ```bash\\n   docker run -u $(id -u):$(id -g) -v $(pwd):/app -w /app node npm install\\n   ```\\n2. **Use gosu in Entrypoint**: Write a wrapper entrypoint script that dynamically maps a custom UID passed as an environment variable to a container user, adjusts file permissions, and steps down to that user using `gosu` before starting the application.",
