    "id": "docker-38",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "Write a custom seccomp profile fragment to block ptrace syscall execution, and explain how this prevents potential container breakout.",
    "answer": "The `ptrace` system call allows a process to trace and control the execution of another process. In container environments, an attacker escaping the namespaces can use ptrace to inject shellcode into host processes.\\n\\nTo block `ptrace` in a custom JSON seccomp profile, you define a rule under `syscalls` that drops or returns `EPERM`:\\n```json\\n{\\n  \"defaultAction\": \"SCMP_ACT_ALLOW\",\\n  \"syscalls\": [\\n    {\\n      \"name\": \"ptrace\",\\n      \"action\": \"SCMP_ACT_ERRNO\",\\n      \"args\": []\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\nRunning the container with this profile `--security-opt seccomp=custom-profile.json` enforces that even if the container runs as root with CAP_SYS_PTRACE, the kernel blocks the syscall, mitigating privilege escalation attacks.",
    "tags": [
      "Security",
      "Seccomp",
      "Privilege Escalation"
    ]
