    "id": "docker-39",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "Walk through the configuration of userns-remap in the Docker daemon, and explain its impact on host storage permissions.",
    "answer": "The `userns-remap` setting maps the container root user (UID 0) to an unprivileged user on the host (e.g., `dockermap`).\\n\\n**Configuration Steps**:\\n1. Ensure subordinate UIDs are allocated in `/etc/subuid`:\\n   `dockermap:100000:65536`\\n2. Configure `/etc/docker/daemon.json`:\\n   ```json\\n   { \"userns-remap\": \"dockermap\" }\\n   ```\\n3. Restart docker: `systemctl restart docker`.\\n\\n**Storage Impact**: Docker will isolate its storage directory `/var/lib/docker/` under a subdirectory owned by the mapped UID/GID (e.g., `/var/lib/docker/100000.100000/`). Any local directory bind mounts will fail or face permission denials unless host paths are explicitly chowned to the mapped UID (100000).",
    "tags": [
      "Security",
      "User Namespaces",
      "userns-remap"
    ]
