    "id": "docker-45",
    "category": "Docker",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "How does Rootless Docker allow binding to privileged ports (< 1024) without root access on the host?",
    "answer": "Traditionally, only UID 0 can bind to ports below 1024. In Rootless Docker, the daemon runs without root privileges.\\n\\nTo bypass this limitation, Rootless Docker utilizes two main approaches:\\n1. **sysctl configuration**: The administrator can set the minimum unprivileged port range on the host:\\n   `sysctl net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=0`\\n   This allows unprivileged host processes to bind to any port.\\n2. **slirp4netns integration**: Rootless Docker routes traffic through a user-space network helper (`slirp4netns`) that creates a TAP interface. It translates TCP/UDP packets into socket calls, simulating connection routing without kernel-level network configuration rights.",
