    "question": "A containerized JVM application exits suddenly without exit code 137. How do you investigate whether the kernel OOM killer was involved, using host system logs?",
    "answer": "Sometimes the kernel OOM killer terminates processes inside the container without terminating the container shim itself immediately, resulting in exit codes other than 137 (like 1 or 143), or the container daemon fails to capture the event.\\n\\n**Investigation Steps**:\\n1. Scan host system logs for kernel OOM messages using `dmesg` or journalctl:\\n   `sudo journalctl -k | grep -i -E 'oom|kill'`\\n2. Look for patterns such as:\\n   `Killed process <pid> (java) total-vm:XXXXkB, anon-rss:XXXXkB, file-rss:0kB`\\n3. Match the killed PID with the container process ID. You can check the container cgroup path in the dmesg output (`/sys/fs/cgroup/system.slice/docker-<id>.scope`) to confirm the exact container target.",
