    "id": "k8s-37",
    "category": "Kubernetes",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How do you enable Encryption at Rest for Secrets stored in etcd using KMS?",
    "answer": "By default, secrets are stored in etcd as unencrypted base64 strings. To encrypt them, you must configure the kube-apiserver with an encryption configuration file.\\n\\n1. Create the `EncryptionConfiguration` file pointing to a KMS provider:\\n   ```yaml\\n   apiVersion: apiserver.config.k8s.io/v1\\n   kind: EncryptionConfiguration\\n   resources:\\n     - resources:\\n         - secrets\\n       providers:\\n         - kms:\\n             name: my-kms-plugin\\n             endpoint: unix:///var/run/kmsprovider.sock\\n             cachesize: 100\\n         - identity: {}\\n   ```\\n2. Mount this file into the `kube-apiserver` static pod manifest and add the flag `--encryption-provider-config=/etc/kubernetes/enc/enc-config.yaml`.\\n3. Restart the API server and execute a rewrite command to encrypt existing secrets: `kubectl get secrets --all-namespaces -o json | kubectl replace -f -`.",
    "tags": [
      "Security",
      "KMS",
      "etcd",
      "Secrets"
    ]
