    "id": "gitlab-25",
    "category": "GitLab",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "What are the top 5 pipeline optimization strategies to reduce GitLab CI build times for a modern web application?",
    "answer": "1. **DAG Scheduling (`needs`)**: Bypass stage barriers so tests run immediately after their respective compile steps.\n2. **Targeted Caching**: Use distinct cache keys with `policy: pull` for testing stages so runners do not re-upload unchanged dependencies.\n3. **Local Docker Registry Cache**: In docker builds, run with `--cache-from` and reference the GitLab Container Registry to reuse pre-built layers:\n   `docker build --cache-from $IMAGE:latest -t $IMAGE:$COMMIT_SHA .`\n4. **Runner Concurrency Tuning**: In `config.toml`, increase CPU/memory limits and set concurrency matching VM host capabilities.\n5. **Kaniko for Docker Build**: Use Kaniko instead of DinD to avoid container virtualization overhead and speed up image publishing operations.",
    "tags": [
      "optimization",
      "caching",
      "kaniko",
      "pipeline design"
    ]
