    "id": "gitlab-33",
    "category": "GitLab",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Explain the purpose of `config.toml` in GitLab Runner. How do you configure `concurrent`, `request_concurrency`, and `volumes` for Docker-in-Docker (DinD) optimization?",
    "answer": "`config.toml` manages runner configuration parameters. For Docker-in-Docker (DinD) setup, you must enable privileged mode and mount storage volumes.\n\n**Example `/etc/gitlab-runner/config.toml`**:\n```toml\nconcurrent = 8  # Global concurrent jobs allowed on this host\n\n[[runners]]\n  name = \"dind-runner\"\n  url = \"https://gitlab.com/\"\n  token = \"GLRT-12345\"\n  executor = \"docker\"\n  [runners.docker]\n    tls_verify = false\n    image = \"docker:20.10-dind\"\n    privileged = true # Required for DinD to run container engine inside container\n    disable_entrypoint_overwrite = false\n    oom_kill_disable = false\n    disable_cache = false\n    volumes = [\"/cache\", \"/certs/client\"]\n```\nCaution: `privileged = true` poses host-level security risks. For secure setups, use Kaniko or mount the host's `/var/run/docker.sock` in volumes instead of running nested Docker engines.",
