    "question": "Explain how to use Triton's Model Analyzer to determine the optimal batch size and concurrency for a model. Provide the command-line usage.",
    "answer": "Triton Model Analyzer runs a series of load tests using Perf Analyzer against a target model under varying concurrency levels, batch sizes, and instance configurations to find the optimal throughput/latency trade-off.\n\nStep 1: Create a `config.yaml` for Model Analyzer:\n```yaml\nmodel_repository: /opt/triton/model_repository\nprofile_models:\n  resnet50_onnx:\n    parameters:\n      concurrency:\n        - 1\n        - 4\n        - 8\n        - 16\n        - 32\n      batch_sizes:\n        - 1\n        - 4\n        - 8\n        - 16\n```\n\nStep 2: Run the Model Analyzer CLI command:\n```bash\nmodel-analyzer profile \\\n  --profile-config-file=config.yaml \\\n  --output-model-repository-path=/opt/triton/output_repo \\\n  --client-protocol=grpc \\\n  --triton-launch-mode=docker\n```\n\nStep 3: Analyze the generated report. It outputs a CSV and PDF plot detailing latency vs. throughput. For instance, it might reveal that a batch size of 8 gives 90% of maximum GPU utilization while keeping the P99 latency under the required 10ms SLA, whereas batch size 16 exceeds the SLA.",
