    "answer": "KServe integrates with Istio. When you create an `InferenceService`, KServe generates underlying Knative Revisions. You can route traffic between these revisions using Istio VirtualServices.\n\nSample Istio VirtualService configuration snippet:\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: networking.istio.io/v1alpha3\nkind: VirtualService\nmetadata:\n  name: model-routing\n  namespace: ml-workloads\nspec:\n  hosts:\n    - model.example.com\n  http:\n  - route:\n    - destination:\n        host: py-model-predictor-default.ml-workloads.svc.cluster.local\n      weight: 90 # Production Champion\n    - destination:\n        host: py-model-canary-predictor-default.ml-workloads.svc.cluster.local\n      weight: 10 # Canary Challenger\n```\n\nDeployment flow:\n1. Deploy the new canary model as a separate deployment or Knative revision.\n2. Apply the VirtualService to intercept the host name and divide the traffic.\n3. Monitor inference error rates and latency. If stable, increase canary weight to 100% and promote.",
