    "id": "mlops-31",
    "category": "MLOps",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "How do you configure GPU time-slicing in a Kubernetes cluster? Provide a ConfigMap example for the NVIDIA Device Plugin.",
    "answer": "GPU time-slicing allows multiple containers to be scheduled on the same physical GPU by time-sharing the execution context. This is configured by creating a ConfigMap containing the sharing replicas and mounting it to the NVIDIA Device Plugin.\n\nStep 1: Create the ConfigMap (`time-slicing-config.yaml`):\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  name: device-plugin-config\n  namespace: kube-system\ndata:\n  any-gpu-name:\n    version: v1\n    sharing:\n      timeSlicing:\n        resources:\n        - name: nvidia.com/gpu\n          replicas: 4 # Expose 1 GPU as 4 logical GPUs\n```\n\nStep 2: Start the device plugin with this config enabled:\n`kubectl set env daemonset/nvidia-device-plugin-daemonset -n kube-system DP_RESOURCE_CONFIG_MAP=device-plugin-config`\n\nLimitations vs. MIG:\nTime-slicing offers no VRAM isolation. If one pod experiences a memory leak, it will consume all physical VRAM and cause all 3 other time-sliced pods sharing that physical GPU to crash with `Out of Memory` errors.",
    "tags": [
      "GPU",
      "Time-slicing",
      "Kubernetes",
      "ConfigMap"
    ]
