    "question": "Describe the architecture of a production-grade RAG data ingestion pipeline. How do you handle chunking, embedding generation, and vector database updates?",
    "answer": "A production-grade ingestion pipeline must process documents at scale, handle updates, and maintain high performance:\n\n1. **Data Ingestion (Apache Spark or Ray)**:\n   - Connectors pull raw documents (PDFs, Markdown, Web Pages) from source stores (S3, Confluence, databases).\n   - Spark/Ray distributes the documents across worker nodes to process files in parallel.\n\n2. **Chunking & Metadata Enrichment**:\n   - Implement semantic chunking (e.g., recursive character splitter) rather than hard character cuts. Typically 512-token chunks with 10% overlap.\n   - Inject metadata into each chunk (author, source URL, timestamp, access control list - ACL).\n\n3. **Distributed Embedding Generation**:\n   - Chunks are grouped into batches and sent to a cluster of local embedding models (e.g., HuggingFace TEI - Text Embeddings Inference running on GPUs) to generate vector representations.\n\n4. **Idempotent Upsert to Vector DB (e.g., Pinecone/Qdrant)**:\n   - Compute a SHA-256 hash of each raw chunk's content to use as the Vector ID.\n   - Upsert (insert or update) the vector and metadata into the DB using this ID. This ensures duplicate documents are not re-indexed and old documents are updated cleanly.",
