    "id": "mlops-43",
    "category": "MLOps",
    "difficulty": "Hard",
    "question": "Design a low-latency, real-time feature extraction pipeline that joins streaming user event data (Kafka) with historical batch features (Snowflake) and writes to Redis with a sub-10ms read SLA.",
    "answer": "To meet a sub-10ms read SLA, the pipeline must calculate heavy aggregations asynchronously and store prepopulated feature vectors in Redis:\n\n1. **Architecture Layout**:\n   - **Data Streams**: User real-time events (e.g., page views, clicks) are published to **Apache Kafka**.\n   - **Stream Processing (Apache Flink)**:\n     - Flink consumes the Kafka stream.\n     - It maintains sliding windows (e.g., click count over last 5m, 1h) in memory using RocksDB state backend.\n     - It outputs aggregate features to **Redis** (Online Store) directly under key `user:<id>:stream_features`.\n   - **Batch Pipeline (Airflow/Snowflake)**:\n     - Snowflake calculates heavy, long-term historical features (e.g., monthly spending, average product categories) nightly.\n     - Airflow runs a sync job to export these features to Redis under key `user:<id>:batch_features`.\n\n2. **Low-Latency Serving Layer (Feature Store Client)**:\n   - The inference service receives a request for `user_123`.\n   - Instead of joining data at query time, the client issues a pipelined Redis `HMGET` command:\n     `HMGET user:123:stream_features user:123:batch_features`\n   - Redis returns both pre-computed vectors in < 2ms.\n   - The inference client concatenates the features in memory and feeds them to the model, meeting the sub-10ms SLA.",
