    "question": "Design a globally distributed, cost-optimized model serving infrastructure on Kubernetes utilizing spot VMs, scale-to-zero autoscaling, and global Anycast load balancing.",
    "answer": "To run model serving globally with low latency and low costs:\n\n1. **Global Anycast Routing (ingress)**:\n   - Deploy a **Global Load Balancer (GLB)** with a single Anycast IP.\n   - Configure GLB to route traffic to the nearest regional Kubernetes cluster (e.g., us-east-1, eu-west-1, ap-northeast-1) based on latency and health checks.\n\n2. **Regional Cluster Setup**:\n   - **Node Pools**: Configure two node pools per cluster:\n     - *System Pool*: Cheap, CPU-only on-demand instances (runs ingress controller, prometheus, Knative control plane).\n     - *GPU Workload Pool*: GPU spot instances (e.g., g4dn/g5 instances on AWS) configured with cluster autoscalers.\n\n3. **Scale-to-Zero serving (Knative)**:\n   - Deploy models using Knative. Set scale-to-zero idle timeout to 5 minutes.\n   - Set local weight caching on nodes (using ReadWriteMany CSI drivers or local SSD caches) to minimize cold-start times when spot VMs scale up.\n\n4. **Failover Routing Policy**:\n   - If a regional cluster loses all GPU Spot capacity (spot eviction storm), the local Prometheus metrics notify the GLB.\n   - The GLB shifts traffic dynamically to the next closest regional cluster with active GPU resources.\n   - Requests are buffered at the Knative Activator proxy in the target cluster while new spot nodes are provisioned.",
