    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "Explain the role and difference between Logstash and Fluentd/Fluent Bit in a log shipping pipeline.",
    "answer": "Both Logstash and Fluentd act as data processors/collectors that read logs from inputs, parse/transform them, and route them to destinations (like Elasticsearch/OpenSearch).\n\nLogstash (ELK native):\n- Written in Ruby/Java, runs on JVM. Can be resource-heavy (high memory footprint).\n- Features: Extremely rich ecosystem of plugins, complex filter capabilities, and native integration with Elasticsearch.\n\nFluentd (CNCF project):\n- Written in Ruby and C. Lighter than Logstash.\n- Fluent Bit: A lightweight C-based alternative to Fluentd designed specifically for containerized, resource-constrained environments (like Kubernetes daemonsets) with minimal memory footprint (~10-20MB vs ~500MB+ for Logstash).\n\nCommon Pattern: SREs deploy Fluent Bit as a daemonset on Kubernetes nodes to collect and ship logs to a centralized Logstash instance or directly to OpenSearch to save resource overhead on nodes.",
