    "id": "obs-35",
    "category": "Observability",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Explain how to define an SLO for a gRPC-based microservice, and write the PromQL SLI expressions for latency and error rate.",
    "answer": "When defining an SLO for a gRPC service, we use gRPC status codes instead of HTTP status codes, and measure request durations.\n\n1. Availability SLO: 99.9% of gRPC requests must succeed (status code must be OK, or expected client errors like `InvalidArgument`).\n- PromQL Availability SLI Expression:\n  `sum(rate(grpc_server_handled_total{grpc_service=\"PaymentService\", grpc_code!~\"(Unknown|Internal|Unavailable|DataLoss)\"}[30d])) / sum(rate(grpc_server_handled_total{grpc_service=\"PaymentService\"}[30d]))`\n\n2. Latency SLO: 99.0% of successful gRPC requests must return in less than 150ms.\n- PromQL Latency SLI Expression:\n  `sum(rate(grpc_server_handling_seconds_bucket{grpc_service=\"PaymentService\", le=\"0.15\", grpc_code=\"OK\"}[30d])) / sum(rate(grpc_server_handling_seconds_count{grpc_service=\"PaymentService\", grpc_code=\"OK\"}[30d]))`\n\nThese queries calculate performance over a rolling 30-day window to evaluate SLO compliance.",
    "tags": [
      "SLI",
      "SLO",
      "gRPC",
      "PromQL"
    ]
