    "id": "tb-12",
    "category": "Troubleshooting",
    "difficulty": "Easy",
    "question": "Clients are reporting SSL certificate errors when connecting to your website. How do you verify the SSL/TLS certificate chain and expiration date from the command line?",
    "answer": "You can inspect remote SSL certificates using `openssl s_client`.\n\n### Diagnostic Steps:\n1. Retrieve the certificate details and print expiration info:\n   `echo | openssl s_client -connect app.example.com:443 -servername app.example.com 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -dates`\n   - Look at `notAfter` to see if the certificate has expired.\n2. Inspect the complete certificate chain (including intermediate certificates):\n   `openssl s_client -connect app.example.com:443 -servername app.example.com -showcerts`\n   - Check if an intermediate CA certificate is missing, which causes some mobile clients or browsers to reject the connection.\n\n### Resolution:\n- If expired, renew the certificate using your CA (e.g., Let's Encrypt / Certbot).\n- Ensure that the certificate file configured in Nginx/Apache includes both the server certificate and the intermediate bundle (fullchain.pem).",
    "tags": [
      "ssl",
      "tls",
      "openssl",
      "certificates"
    ]
