    "question": "Write a Bash script that checks if port 8080 is listening on localhost. If it is not, the script must start a dummy netcat listener on port 8080 in the background and log a start message.",
    "answer": "You can check port status using `nc` (netcat) or `ss` and act conditionally.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nHOST=\"127.0.0.1\"\nPORT=8080\n\n# Check if port is listening using nc (zero-I/O mode -z)\nif nc -z \"${HOST}\" \"${PORT}\"; then\n    echo \"Port ${PORT} is already listening on ${HOST}.\"\nelse\n    echo \"Port ${PORT} is not listening. Starting dummy listener...\"\n    # Start netcat listening in background, redirect outputs to null\n    nc -l \"${HOST}\" \"${PORT}\" > /dev/null 2>&1 &\n    echo \"Dummy listener started in background (PID: $!).\"\nfi\n```",
