    "question": "Write a Bash helper function `check_dependencies` that takes a list of CLI command names (e.g., `docker`, `kubectl`, `git`) and verifies if they are executable and available in the current environment's `PATH`. Exit the script if any dependency is missing.",
    "answer": "In Bash, you should use `command -v` to check command existence instead of `which`, as `command` is a shell built-in and more portable.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\n\ncheck_dependencies() {\n  local missing=0\n  for cmd in \"$@\"; do\n    # command -v returns 0 if command exists, non-zero otherwise\n    if ! command -v \"${cmd}\" >/dev/null 2>&1; then\n      echo \"[ERROR] Missing dependency: ${cmd} is not installed or not in PATH.\" >&2\n      missing=$((missing + 1))\n    fi\n  done\n  \n  if [[ \"${missing}\" -gt 0 ]]; then\n    echo \"[FATAL] Please install missing dependencies and try again.\" >&2\n    exit 1\n  fi\n}\n\n# Test the function\ncheck_dependencies docker kubectl git\necho \"All dependencies verified!\"\n```",
