    "question": "Write a Bash script pattern that uses `flock` to ensure a cron job script cannot run concurrently. If another instance of the script is already active, the new instance must log a warning and exit immediately with status 0 (no error).",
    "answer": "You can use `flock` with a dedicated lock file descriptor to achieve concurrency control.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nLOCKFILE=\"/var/run/my_cron_job.lock\"\n# Open the lockfile on file descriptor 9\nexec 9>>\"${LOCKFILE}\"\n\n# Attempt to acquire an exclusive lock non-blockingly (-n)\nif ! flock -n 9; then\n    echo \"[WARN] Another instance of the script is already running. Exiting gracefully.\" >&2\n    exit 0\nfi\n\n# Lock acquired successfully! Script logic goes here.\necho \"[INFO] Lock acquired. Executing critical tasks...\"\nsleep 10\necho \"[INFO] Tasks complete. Releasing lock.\"\n```",
