    "question": "Write a Bash script that concurrently downloads a list of 10 large backup files in the background using curl. The script must wait for all background downloads to finish and check if all exited with status 0.",
    "answer": "You can use Bash's background operator `&` and track the process IDs (PIDs) using the `wait` command.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nurls=(\n  \"https://example.com/backup1.tar.gz\"\n  \"https://example.com/backup2.tar.gz\"\n  \"https://example.com/backup3.tar.gz\"\n)\n\ndeclare -A pids\n\nfor url in \"${urls[@]}\"; do\n    filename=$(basename \"${url}\")\n    echo \"[START] Downloading ${filename} in background...\"\n    curl -sS -o \"${filename}\" \"${url}\" &\n    # Capture the PID of the last background command\n    pids[\"${filename}\"]=$!\ndone\n\nfailures=0\n\n# Wait for each process individually to retrieve its exit code\nfor filename in \"${!pids[@]}\"; do\n    pid=${pids[\"${filename}\"]}\n    if wait \"${pid}\"; then\n        echo \"[SUCCESS] Downloaded ${filename}\"\n    else\n        echo \"[FAILED] Download for ${filename} (PID: ${pid}) failed!\" >&2\n        failures=$((failures + 1))\n    fi\ndone\n\nif [[ \"${failures}\" -gt 0 ]]; then\n    echo \"[ERROR] ${failures} downloads failed.\" >&2\n    exit 1\nfi\necho \"All downloads completed successfully.\"\n```",
