    "question": "Write a complex `awk` script to process a CSV file `billing.csv` (which has columns `Host,Service,Region,Cost`). The script must sum the costs grouped by region and output the results as `Region: TotalCost` only for regions where the total cost is greater than $1000.",
    "answer": "You can use `awk`'s associative arrays and its `END` execution block to aggregate and filter data.\n\n### Bash Command:\n`awk -F, 'NR > 1 { cost[$3] += $4 } END { for (r in cost) { if (cost[r] > 1000) printf \"%s: $%.2f\\n\", r, cost[r] } }' billing.csv`\n\n### Explanation:\n- `-F,`: Sets the field separator to a comma for parsing CSV.\n- `NR > 1`: Skips the CSV header row (Number of Record > 1).\n- `cost[$3] += $4`: Aggregates the cost (column 4) into an associative array indexed by the region name (column 3).\n- `END`: Executes this block after reading all lines.\n- `for (r in cost)`: Iterates over each region stored in the array.\n- `if (cost[r] > 1000)`: Filters out regions with cost <= 1000.",
