    "category": "Scripting",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Write a custom log-rotation shell script in Bash. It should check if `/var/log/app.log` exceeds 100 Megabytes. If it does, rotate it by appending a timestamp, keep only the latest 5 rotated logs, compress them with gzip, and recreate `/var/log/app.log` with the correct permissions.",
    "answer": "You can write a rotation script using file size checks, loops, and standard utilities.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nLOG_FILE=\"/var/log/app.log\"\nMAX_SIZE=$((100 * 1024 * 1024)) # 100MB in bytes\nBACKUP_DIR=\"/var/log/\"\nTIMESTAMP=$(date +\"%Y%m%d%H%M%S\")\n\nif [[ -f \"${LOG_FILE}\" && $(stat -c%s \"${LOG_FILE}\") -gt ${MAX_SIZE} ]]; then\n    echo \"Log file size exceeds 100MB. Starting rotation...\"\n    \n    # Rotate active log\n    ROTATED_FILE=\"${LOG_FILE}.${TIMESTAMP}\"\n    mv \"${LOG_FILE}\" \"${ROTATED_FILE}\"\n    \n    # Recreate log file\n    touch \"${LOG_FILE}\"\n    chmod 0640 \"${LOG_FILE}\"\n    \n    # Compress in background\n    gzip \"${ROTATED_FILE}\" &\n    \n    # Keep only the latest 5 rotated logs\n    ls -t ${LOG_FILE}.*.gz 2>/dev/null | tail -n +6 | while read -r old_log; do\n        echo \"Deleting old log: ${old_log}\"\n        rm -f \"${old_log}\"\n    done\nfi\n```",
