    "question": "Write a Bash script that sends a formatted Slack notification containing deployment details (service name, git hash, status) as a JSON payload to a Slack Webhook URL using `curl`. Safely handle double quotes in input variables.",
    "answer": "When constructing JSON payloads dynamically in Bash, you should use `jq` to build the payload rather than string concatenation, to prevent JSON formatting syntax errors caused by double quotes or special characters in variables.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nWEBHOOK_URL=\"https://hooks.slack.com/services/T00/B00/X00\"\nSERVICE_NAME=\"checkout-api\"\nGIT_COMMIT=\"9a5e8f498c8c7\"\nDEPLOY_STATUS=\"SUCCESSFUL - Stable\"\n\n# Construct JSON safely using jq to handle escaping\nPAYLOAD=$(jq -n \\\n  --arg service \"${SERVICE_NAME}\" \\\n  --arg commit \"${GIT_COMMIT}\" \\\n  --arg status \"${DEPLOY_STATUS}\" \\\n  '{\n    text: \"Deployment Notification\",\n    attachments: [{\n      color: \"#36a64f\",\n      fields: [\n        {title: \"Service\", value: $service, short: true},\n        {title: \"Commit Hash\", value: $commit, short: true},\n        {title: \"Status\", value: $status, short: false}\n      ]\n    }]\n  }')\n\n# Send to Slack webhook\ncurl -s -X POST -H \"Content-type: application/json\" --data \"${PAYLOAD}\" \"${WEBHOOK_URL}\"\n```",
