    "question": "In a minimal container environment where `jq` is not installed, write a Bash pipeline using `grep` or `sed` to extract the value of the key `\"status\"` (e.g. `\"UP\"` or `\"DOWN\"`) from a flat JSON payload returned by an HTTP health check endpoint: `{\"service\":\"db\",\"status\":\"UP\",\"checks\":10}`.",
    "answer": "Without `jq`, you can parse flat JSON using regular expression capturing groups in `sed` or `grep -oP`.\n\n### Using sed Capture Groups:\n`curl -s http://localhost:8080/health | sed -n 's/.*\"status\"\\s*:\\s*\"\\([^\"]*\\)\".*/\\1/p'`\n\n### Using grep with PCRE regex (-P):\n`curl -s http://localhost:8080/health | grep -oP '(?<=\"status\"\\s*:\\s*\")[^\"]+'`\n\n### Explanation of grep pattern:\n- `(?<=\"status\"\\s*:\\s*\")`: Lookbehind assertion verifying the match is preceded by the key `status`, optional spaces, a colon, and an opening double quote.\n- `[^\"]+`: Matches one or more characters that are not a closing double quote (i.e., capturing the value string itself).",
