    "id": "code-35",
    "category": "Scripting",
    "difficulty": "Intermediate",
    "question": "Write a Bash automation script to check if a local SSH private key file `~/.ssh/id_ed25519` exists. If not, generate a new Ed25519 key pair without prompting the user for input. Then loop over a file `hosts.txt` containing target server IPs and push the key using `ssh-copy-id` (handling credentials login bypass).",
    "answer": "You can generate keys silently using the `-N` passphrase flag and `-f` destination flag with `ssh-keygen`.\n\n### Bash Script:\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nKEY_PATH=\"${HOME}/.ssh/id_ed25519\"\nHOSTS_FILE=\"hosts.txt\"\n\n# 1. Generate SSH Key if it doesn't exist\nif [[ ! -f \"${KEY_PATH}\" ]]; then\n    echo \"SSH Key not found. Generating Ed25519 keypair...\"\n    ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -N \"\" -f \"${KEY_PATH}\"\nfi\n\n# 2. Distribute key to hosts\nif [[ -f \"${HOSTS_FILE}\" ]]; then\n    while read -r host; do\n        # Skip empty lines or commented lines\n        [[ -z \"${host}\" || \"${host}\" =~ ^# ]] && continue\n        \n        echo \"Pushing key to host: ${host}...\"\n        # ssh-copy-id copies key to remote authorized_keys\n        # StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new auto-accepts new SSH host keys\n        ssh-copy-id -i \"${KEY_PATH}\" -o StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new \"ubuntu@${host}\"\n    done < \"${HOSTS_FILE}\"\nelse\n    echo \"[ERROR] Hosts file ${HOSTS_FILE} not found!\" >&2\n    exit 1\nfi\n```",
    "tags": [
      "bash",
      "ssh",
      "automation",
      "security"
    ]
